    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-07-20T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-07-20T15:00:00-05:00" n="730"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d730">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.5034 China—Searchlight Publishing Co./9:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Shanghai (<persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_CES1" type="to"
                            >Cunningham</persName>)</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-07-20T16:00:00-04:00"
                            >July 20, 1932—4 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>223. Your 336, July 14, 9 a.m.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>You should ask <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_IHR1">Isaacs</persName> to
                        call at the Consulate General and inform him (<hi rend="italic">a</hi>) that
                        his campaign of criticism and vilification of the Chinese Government, which
                        may reasonably be interpreted as an attempt to incite rebellion against that
                        Government, is a gross abuse of his privilege as an American citizen
                        residing in China and is seriously prejudicial to the interests of the
                        United States and its nationals in China; (<hi rend="italic">b</hi>) that
                        the Chinese authorities have properly complained of his attacks on the
                        Government of China and have requested the suppression of his offending
                        publication; (<hi rend="italic">c</hi>) that he has forfeited any right of
                        protection by the Government of the United States with respect to his
                        publication and, if the present policy of that publication is continued, the
                        registration of the Searchlight Publishing Company as an American enterprise
                        will be cancelled and this Government will not intervene to prevent action
                        by the Chinese authorities against his publication for the purpose of
                        suppressing it.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Inform the Legation.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1932v03#p_SHL1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
